I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and connecting with artists. They aren't burdened by the pressure to view everything through a critical lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but today, that collective awareness has disappeared.
At that time, we could directly immerse ourselves in the content without worrying about its source, because tracking down the origin was not easy back then.
We revere these artists almost like gods, and there is no reason to question this worship. As a result, we establish a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, regarding them as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so fond of nostalgia.
When the TV show "The Office" was still airing, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together while eating pizza.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming platforms typically release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches them at their own pace. When posting about the plot on social media, people often add a "spoiler warning," or simply discuss the show in specific groups.
Unconsciously, we all long to relive that sense of collective belonging that connects everyone.
It is precisely because of our nostalgia that we keep rewatching TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," whose unforgettable lines spread online like memes.
We would quote classic lines from these works and believe that most people would understand them implicitly.
Nowadays, even if something becomes popular online, we can't assume that everyone has seen it.
Nowadays, there's an information explosion, and there are simply too many things that require our attention, making it impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape from this state of information overload?
Time and again, we discover new media and new artists, only to find that they are either notorious sexual predators or stubborn bigots filled with prejudice—an endless cycle that grows increasingly tiresome.
On one hand, we are deeply immersed in nostalgia, yet on the other hand, we cannot help but acknowledge that the people who created the artworks we cherish may have serious moral flaws. This contradictory mindset leaves us feeling helpless and conflicted.
We will be even more careful in building "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that if a person wants to gain wealth and power, it becomes very difficult to ensure that they will not harm or take advantage of others.
Because the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who still remain stubbornly deluded, insisting on elevating others to the status of a god; when the idol eventually falls, they pretend to be utterly shocked.
We are living in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
